It’s the end of the racing season and the holidays are approaching quickly. Now is the time you might be considering upgrading your equipment, whether by updating a groupset or buying a brand-new bike altogether.

The blizzard of information, potential or promised benefits, and the wide range of options on the market can leave you confused or frustrated with a purchase that simply isn’t right for you.

Today on the Purple Patch Podcast, IRONMAN Master Coach Matt Dixon welcomes Chris Soden of IOG Bike Fit & Consulting to the show. With over 25 years in the cycling industry and an extensive background as a professional bike fitter and industry consultant, Chris shares his in-depth knowledge to help you wade through the difficult decisions athletes and fitness enthusiasts of all levels face when considering their next bike purchase.

Matt and Chris discuss five key elements to consider if you’re debating upgrading your bike, buying a new bike, or even thinking about getting a used bike — as well as how you can ensure your bike fit is dialed in, and be confident that you’re investing in the right equipment for you.

Listen to the full episode at the PODCAST link in our bio.

In this episode of the Purple Patch Podcast, Matt provides a game plan to help you build your resilience and bolster your immune system to avoid sickness — and to minimize the impact if you do end up under the weather. He offers insight into illness prevention through a coach’s lens, using peer-reviewed research, and the expertise of medical and sport professionals.

He discusses the simple but effective basic supporting habit you can use to build up your defense, how to approach your training to ensure you remain helathy, and other tips and tricks to apply should you start to feel symptoms.

"IT MAKES ME A BETTER ME"

"Last Sunday I finished up an extended triathlon season with my third half-iron distance race of the year at Florida 70.3.

Objectively the numbers speak for themselves: my fastest half marathon (stand-alone or in a triathlon) and 20 seconds away from being top 5 in my age group. 

Subjectively it’s harder to put into words how successful this was. Physically, mentally, and emotionally this was a good race. I can now actually execute race plans instead of just trying to get through a race. And none of this is at the expense of anything else in my life: family, work, friends, experiences, health. That’s saying a lot for someone with an incredibly demanding and stressful job that put her away from home in random places for more than 60 nights this year. 

And I think it actually enriches those other areas of my life; it makes me a better me. 

My secret? Consistency. Patience. Perspective. How do I do that? With help from my coach John Stevens at Purple Patch Fitness, and the Fuelin team." 

- Purple Patch 1:1 athlete Amy Gray, coached by John Stevens

We’ve got a special podcast for you this week. This is a must-listen for athletes and coaches of all levels.

This week, we invite two special guests onto the show to explore the critical yet often undervalued process of post-event decompression and assessment.

The post-event experience is a huge part of the fabric of your athletic journey. Win, lose or draw, it can be a confusing and destabilizing time filled with distractions and complex emotions, both positive and negative. There is a natural desire to analyze your performance, find answers, process and move on to the next big thing.

In today’s discussion, Matt welcomes sports psychologists Sarah Cecil and Dr. Danielle Adams Norenberg for an in-depth discussion around Emotional Decompression, a model to navigate emotions following a major race or event.

Danielle and Sarah both have extensive experience working with British Olympic athletes across various sports, and set out to create a process for athletes to properly digest the experience and re-engage with the athletic journey and life in a healthy way.

With their help, Matt takes a closer look at the evolving role of psychology in sport through the lens of their work with world-class athletes, and the essential need to structure the process around the post-event experience. Together they break down the model of decompression step by step to deliver a highly accessible and actionable process that is sure to become an essential part of your performance journey.

Check out the video podcast at the link in our bio or catch Episode 252 of the Purple Patch Podcast on your favorite listening app.

The harsh truth: you can be the best runner in the world -- but if you blow it on the bike, you'll never get to showcase your talent.

If you tend to underperform on the run, you might ask yourself:

- Do I know my actual fueling and electrolyte needs? Did I fuel properly race morning, and did I actually execute my fueling and hydration plan from breakfast all the way through T2?
- How did my swim go? Did I expend excess energy due to open water anxiety, poor sighting technique, or swimming off course?
- Am I coming into the run with muscle fatigue due to poor bike fit or posture?
- How's my form on the bike, and how sharpened are my bike skills? Am I wasting energy on an inefficient pedal stroke, carrying tension when cornering or descending, or spiking my heart rate on hills?
- How well did I pace my bike? Do I blindly riding to a set power number, regardless of terrain, wind, or my internal sense of effort? Have I honed my internal sense of how much 'gas is left in the tank' and where to push or scale back?

Triathlon is one sport, not three. Rather than simply thinking that you've underperformed on the run, reframe it as "I underperformed at the end of my triathlon". This small shift in mindset can illuminate new ways for you to improve your overall performance and get to the finish line feeling strong.
